ti]] International, Brussels, Belgium, 1994\n* ''Sudan \u2013 Refugees in their own country: The Forced Relocation of Squatters and Displaced People from Khartoum'', in Volume 4, Issue 10, of News from Africa Watch, 10 July 1992.\n* ''Human Rights Violations in Sudan'', by the Sudan Human Rights Organization, February 1994. [accounts of widespread torture, ethnic cleansing and crucifixion of pastors].\n* ''Pax Romana statement of Macram Max Gassis, Bishop of [[Al-Ubayyid|El Obeid]]'', to the Fiftieth Session of the UN Commission on Human Rights, Geneva, February 1994 [accounts of widespread destruction of hundreds of churches, forced conversions of Christians to Islam, [[concentration camps]], genocide of the [[Nuba]] people, systematic rape of women, enslavement of children, torture of priests and clerics, burning alive of pastors and catechists, crucifixion and mutilation of priests].\n* The Persian conquest of Jerusalem in 614CE compared with Islamic conquest of 638CE\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Mileusni\u0107|first=Slobodan|title=Spiritual Genocide: A survey of destroyed, damaged and desecrated churches, monasteries and other church buildings during the war 1991\u20131995 (1997)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_TaPAAAAMAAJ|year=1997|location=Belgrade|publisher=Museum of the Serbian Orthodox Church}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Pavlowitch|first=Stevan K.|authorlink=Stevan K. Pavlowitch|title=Serbia: The History behind the Name|year=2002|location=London|publisher=Hurst & Company|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w-RuLDaNwbMC|isbn=9781850654773}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wand |first=John Williams Charles |author-link=John William Charles Wand |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ci2hvwXqlKMC |title=A History of the Early Church to AD 500 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=1990 |pages=320 |isbn=9780203131145 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Persecution of Christians}}\n* [http://www.intoleranceagainstchristians.eu/ Observatory on Intolerance and Discrimination Against Christians in Europe]\n* [http://www.persecution.org International Christian Concern: Daily News on Christian Persecution around the World]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181118042143/http://www.montagnard-foundation.org/ Montagnard Foundation supporting Christians persecuted in Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia]\n* [http://www.ryanspencerreed.com/ Photojournalist's Account] \u2013 Images of Sudan's persecution\n\n{{Persecution of Christians}}\n{{Christianity footer}}\n{{Religious persecution}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Persecution Of Christians}}\n[[Category:Persecution of Christians| ]]\n[[Category:Persecution by Hindus]]\n[[Category:Persecution of Christians by Muslims| ]]\n[[Category:Religious persecution by communists|Christians]]\n", "name_user": "Tgeorgescu", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persecution_of_Christians"}
{"title_page": "Mainwal", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=February 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Mainwal\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| settlement_type         = Village\n| pushpin_map             = India Punjab#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Punjab, India\n| coordinates             = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Jalandhar district|Jalandhar]]\n| subdivision_type3       = Tehsil\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Phillaur]]\n| subdivision_type4       = Region\n| subdivision_name4       = \n| government_type         = [[Panchayati raj (India)|Panchayat raj]]\n| governing_body          = [[Gram panchayat]]\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref>tags -->\n| elevation_m             = \n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_blank2_title = Total Households\n| population_blank2      = 412\n| population_footnotes    =\n| population_total        = 1963<br/><small>981/982 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]</small>\n| population_density_km2  = \n| population_note         = \n| population_blank1_title = Scheduled Castes\n| population_blank1      = 1248<br/><small>627/621 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]</small>\n| population_demonym      = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n| demographics1_title2    = \n| demographics1_info2     = \n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_total_ha           = 688\n| area_code_type          = Telephone\n| area_code               = 01826\n| registration_plate      = PB-37\n| iso_code                = IN-PB\n| blank1_name_sec2        = \n| blank1_info_sec2        = \n| website                 = {{URL|Jalandhar.gov.in}}\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n'''Mainwal''' is a village in [[Phillaur]] in [[Jalandhar district]] of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] [[States and territories of India|State]], India. It is located {{convert|8|km}} from sub district headquarter and {{convert|40|km}} from district headquarter. The village is [[Administration (government)|administrated]] by [[Sarpanch]] an elected representative of the village.\n\n== Demography ==\n{{as of|2011}}, The village has a total number of 412 houses and the population of 1963 of which 981 are males while 982 are females.<ref name=census>{{cite web|url=https://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_Village_Release_0300.xlsx|title=DCHB Village Release|work=[[Census of India, 2011]]}}</ref>  According to the report [[published]] by [[Census India]] in 2011, out of the total population of the village 1248 people are from [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Schedule Caste]] and the village does not have any [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Schedule Tribe]] population so far.<ref name=census />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of villages in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180608165116/http://punjabtourism.gov.in/ Tourism of Punjab]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180804201629/http://punjabcensus.gov.in/ Census of Punjab]\n{{Jalandhar district}}\n\n{{coord missing|Punjab (India)}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Jalandhar district]]\n\n\n{{Jalandhar-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=February 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Mainwal\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| settlement_type         = Village\n| pushpin_map             = India Punjab#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Punjab, India\n| coordinates             = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Jalandhar district|Jalandhar]]\n| subdivision_type3       = Tehsil\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Phillaur]]\n| subdivision_type4       = Region\n| subdivision_name4       = \n| government_type         = [[Panchayati raj (India)|Panchayat raj]]\n| governing_body          = [[Gram panchayat]]\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref>tags -->\n| elevation_m             = \n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_blank2_title = Total Households\n| population_blank2      = 412\n| population_footnotes    =\n| population_total        = 1963<br/><small>981/982 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]</small>\n| population_density_km2  = \n| population_note         = \n| population_blank1_title = Scheduled Castes\n| population_blank1      = 1248<br/><small>627/621 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]</small>\n| population_demonym      = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n| demographics1_title2    = \n| demographics1_info2     = \n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_total_ha           = 688\n| area_code_type          = Telephone\n| area_code               = 01826\n| registration_plate      = PB-37\n| iso_code                = IN-PB\n| blank1_name_sec2        = \n| blank1_info_sec2        = \n| website                 = {{URL|Jalandhar.gov.in}}\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n'''Mainwal''' is a village in [[Phillaur]] in [[Jalandhar district]] of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] [[States and territories of India|State]], India. It is located {{convert|8|km}} from sub district headquarter and {{convert|40|km}} from district headquarter. The village is [[Administration (government)|administrated]] by [[Sarpanch]] an elected representative of the village.\n\n== Demography ==\n{{as of|2011}}, The village has a total number of 412 houses and the population of 1963 of which 981 are males while 982 are females.<ref name=census>{{cite web|url=https://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_Village_Release_0300.xlsx|title=DCHB Village Release|work=[[Census of India, 2011]]}}</ref>  According to the report [[published]] by [[Census India]] in 2011, out of the total population of the village 1248 people are from [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Schedule Caste]] and the village does not have any [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Schedule Tribe]] population so far.<ref name=census />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of villages in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180608165116/http://punjabtourism.gov.in/ Tourism of Punjab]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180804201629/http://punjabcensus.gov.in/ Census of Punjab]\n{{Jalandhar district}}\n\n{{coord missing|Punjab (India)}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Jalandhar district]]\n\n\n{{PunjabIN-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SDZeroBot", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stub sorting: replacing PunjabIN-geo-stub with Jalandhar-geo-stub", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mainwal"}
{"title_page": "Bobby Richardson", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{about|the baseball player|the football player|Bobby Richardson (American football)|the North Carolina politician|Bobbie Richardson}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Bobby Richardson\n|image=Bobby Richardson - New York Yankees.jpg\n|caption=Richardson, circa 1964\u201366\n|position=[[Second baseman]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1935|8|19}}\n|birth_place=[[Sumter, South Carolina]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=August 5\n|debutyear=1955\n|debutteam=New York Yankees\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 2\n|finalyear=1966\n|finalteam=New York Yankees\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.266\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=34\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=390\n|teams=\n* [[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|1955}}\u2013{{mlby|1966}})\n|highlights=\n* 8\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1957 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1957]], [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1959\u00b2]], [[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1962]]\u2013[[1966 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1966]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1958}}, {{wsy|1961}}, {{wsy|1962}})\n* [[World Series MVP]] (1960)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (1961\u20131965)\n}}\n'''Robert Clinton Richardson, Jr.''' (born August 19, 1935) is a former [[second baseman]] in [[Major League Baseball]] who played for the [[New York Yankees]] from {{Baseball year|1955}} through {{Baseball year|1966}}. Batting and throwing right-handed, he was a superb defensive infielder, as well as something of a clutch hitter, who played a large role in the Yankee baseball dynasty of his day. He is the only [[World Series MVP Award|World Series MVP]] ever to be selected from the losing team. He wore the uniform number 1 for the majority of his career (1958\u20131966).\n\n==Early life==\nRichardson was the middle child of Robert Sr. and Debbie Richardson of [[Sumter, South Carolina]]. He had two sisters, Inez (older) and Willie Ann (younger).<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Richardson Marble and Granite Works in Sumter was managed by Robert Sr., who also owned some of the interest in the company.<ref name=\"Richardson's father\">{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1963/06/18/80711961.html?pageNumber=37|title=Bobby Richardson's Father, 57|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 1963|accessdate=April 10, 2020|page=37}}</ref>\n\nGrowing up, Richardson practiced his baseball skills with Harry Stokes, a boy in his neighborhood seven years his senior who would play catch with him. Richardson played on a local [[YMCA]]/[[Salvation Army]] team at the age of ten. Later, he played on ballclubs sponsored by the local [[Kiwanis Club]] and [[American Legion]]. On the American Legion team, Richardson's coach was [[Fred Hutchinson]], who would later manage the [[Cincinnati Reds]] when Richardson faced them in the [[1961 World Series]]. Hutchinson and Richardson became American Legion champions in 1952, Richardson's junior year of high school. Hutchinson also coached Richardson at Edmunds High School.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n11 out of 16 [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) teams showed interest in Richardson, as well as the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] and [[Georgia Tech University]], which offered baseball scholarships. [[Mayo Smith]], manager of the [[Norfolk Tars]], a team in the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Piedmont League]] and an affiliate of the [[New York Yankees]], scouted Richardson for New York, as did Bill Harris. Ultimately, Richardson decided to forgo college and sign with the Yankees out of high school (though he later earned a degree in accounting).<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Sunday Conversation\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nRichardson started his [[Minor league baseball|minor league]] career in 1953 with the [[Norfolk Tars]] of the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Piedmont League]], travelling by bus to Norfolk from Sumter with $85 in coins friends and family had given him.<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web|last=Pasculli|first=Len|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/47363efd|title=Bobby Richardson|work=SABR|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> After Richardson [[Batting average|batted]] just .211 in his first 27 games with the Tars, the Yankees assigned him to a [[Class D (baseball)|Class D]] team, the [[Olean Yankees]] of the [[New York\u2013Penn League|PONY League]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"minors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=richar007rob|title=Bobby Richardson Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> With Olean, he batted .412 in 32 games and hit his first [[home run]].<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nIn 1954, Richardson was promoted, heading up to the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[Binghamton Triplets]] of the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] without having to return to Norfolk. Spending the whole year in Binghamton, he ranked among the Eastern League leaders in games (141, tied for first), [[Runs scored|runs]] (81, fifth), 171 [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] (first), [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (29, second to Clyde Parris's 40), and batting average (.310, second to Parris's .313).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=af825f91|title=1954 Eastern League Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> For his contributions, Richardson was named the Eastern League's [[Most Valuable Player]] (MVP).<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nRichardson spent most of [[spring training]] with the Yankees in 1955 but was sent to the [[Class AAA (baseball)|Class AAA]] [[Denver Bears]] of the [[American Association (20th Century)|American Assocation]] to start the year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=31|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1955/04/01/85690101.html?pageNumber=31|title=Five Players Cut From Squad Before Yanks Start Northward|work=The New York Times|date=April 1, 1955|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> In 119 games with the Bears, he batted .296 with 146 hits, 99 runs scord, 21 doubles, 12 [[Triple (baseball)|triples]], six home runs, and 59 RBI.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nWhen [[Gil McDougald]] found himself on the receiving end of a [[line drive]] during [[batting practice]] in August of 1955, the Yankees called up Richardson.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He debuted on August 5, 1955, getting his first hit against [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Jim Bunning]] in a 3\u20130 victory over the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In the field, he was a \"nervous wreck\" as he later described, but no balls were hit to him.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bobby Richardson Story|first=Bobby |last=Richardson |location=Old Tappan, New Jersey|publisher=Fleming H. Revell Co.|year=1965|page=84}}</ref> He started four games at second base in three days (including an August 7 [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]]), then entered three games in the late innings at [[shortstop]] before getting sent to the minor leagues on August 15 to make room for a [[pitcher]] returning from the [[disabled list]].<ref name=\"1955 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Drebinger|first=John|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1955/08/16/79451253.html?pageNumber=26|title=Home Runs Mark 5\u20134, 12\u20136 Triumphs|work=The New York Times|date=August 16, 1955|accessdate=April 10, 2020|page=26}}</ref> For some reason, he was sent to the [[Richmond Virginians]] of the Class AAA [[International League]] this time, with whom he finished the season.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Called up again in [[September call-up|September]], he appeared in four more games for the Yankees before the end of the year.<ref name=\"1955 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1955|title=Bobby Richardson 1955 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, Richardson started the season with the Yankees. However, he only appeared in five games for them, batting .143 before getting sent back to Denver May 13.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=42|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/05/14/93203323.html?pageNumber=42|title=Bombers Win, 11\u20132; Drop 5\u20131 Decision|work=The New York Times|date=May 14, 1956|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> With the Bears, he ranked among the American Association leaders in batting average (.328, third), runs scored (102, sixth), hits (175, fourth), doubles (30, ninth), and triples (12, tied with [[Willie Kirkland]] for second behind [[Larry Raines]]'s 14).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=62cbeec8|title=1956 American Association Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRichardson made the team in 1957 and took over the second base job from [[Billy Martin]], the Yankees' volatile infielder who injured himself in a deliberate golf cart collision with [[Mickey Mantle]] in spring training, then got into a highly-publicized brawl at the [[Copacabana (nightclub)|Copacabana Club]] in May before getting traded to the [[Kansas City Athletics]] in June.<ref name=\"Silence\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=34|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/06/25/84738480.html?pageNumber=34|title=Silence! Bobby Richardson at Work|work=The New York Times|date=June 25, 1957|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Golenbock|first=Peter|origyear=1994|title=Wild, High and Tight: The Life and Death of Billy Martin|publisher=Antenna Books|edition=Kindle version of Antenna Books ebook |page=2631\u20132644 |location=New York|year=2014|isbn=978-1-62306-022-0|ref={{sfnRef|Golenbock}}}}</ref> Richardson proved a quieter sort of character, if not a great hitter in 1957; manager [[Casey Stengel]] said, \"Look at him. He doesn't drink, he doesn't smoke, he doesn't chew, he doesn't stay out late, and he still can't hit .250.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His fielding was better; [[Louis Effrat]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote June 25, \"He has thrilled the fans with his great stops and catches...no one gets rid of the ball quicker [on [[double play]]s].\"<ref name=\"Silence\"/> Actually, Richardson's .331 average trailed only Mantle among the Yankees on June 25,<ref name=\"Silence\"/> and he made his first appearance in the [[1957 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] that year.<ref name=\"reference\"/> However, he batted .188 over the rest of the year, finishing the season with a .256 mark and 78 hits in 305 [[at bat]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1957|title=Bobby Richardson 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy September, Richardson was losing a lot of starts to [[Jerry Coleman]] at second base.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=colemje01&t=b&year=1957|title=Jerry Coleman 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Even so, Stengel waited until the last minute to decide whether Coleman or Richardson would start at second base in the [[1957 World Series]] against the [[Milwaukee Braves]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/10/01/91165032.html?pageNumber=54|title=Mantle's Status Remains in Doubt|work=The New York Times|date=October 1, 1957|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Ultimately, Stengel chose Coleman, who started all seven games for the Yankees as Richardson was limited to two appearances as a [[pinch-runner]] and [[defensive replacement]].<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Coleman\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=colemje01&t=b&year=0&post=1|title=Jerry Coleman Postseason Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees lost the Series in seven games.<ref name=\"Postseason Coleman\"/>\n\nColeman retired following the 1957 season, and Richardson began 1958 as the Yankees' starting second baseman.<ref>{{cite web|last=McGowen|first=Roscoe|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/11/22/90856130.html?pageNumber=38|page=38|title=Coleman Retires as Player After Nine Years with Yankees|work=The New York Times|date=November 22, 1957|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> After batting .203 through the Yankees' first 18 games, he missed 20 in a row as McDougald began getting the starts at second.<ref name=\"1958 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1958|title=Bobby Richardson 1958 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mcdougi01&t=b&year=1958|title=Gil McDougald 1958 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Richardson started at second from June 5 through June 12 but thereafter spent most of the season on the bench until September, when he again got a few starts at second base.<ref name=\"1958 Richardson\"/> In 73 games (182 at bats), he batted .247 with 18 runs scored and 45 hits.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Richardson considered quitting baseball that season because of his struggles, but [[Ralph Houk]], the Yankees' [[General manager (baseball)|general manager]] and Richardson's former manager at Denver, convinced him to keep playing.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In the [[1958 World Series]], again against the Braves, Richardson finished three games for the Yankees at [[third base]] and also started Game 4 at third, though he was hitless in two at bats before getting pinch-hit for in the seventh by [[Elston Howard]].<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=0&post=1|title=Bobby Richardson Postseason Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA195810050.shtml|title=1958 World Series Game 4, Braves at Yankees, October 5|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> However, he became a World Series champion for the first time as this year, the Yankees defeated the Braves in seven games.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nRichardson began 1959 as the Yankees' shortstop; Effrat wrote, \"[Richardson] is a tremendous fielder no matter where [the Yankees] play him.\"<ref name=\"Kiely\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/04/20/89183045.html?pageNumber=37|title=Kiely Is Credited with 5\u20134 Victory|work=The New York Times|page=37|date=April 20, 1959|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He moved to second base on April 18 after McDougald suffered cracked knuckles, then returned to shortstop on April 29 when McDougald returned to the lineup.<ref name=\"Kiely\"/><ref name=\"1959 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1959|title=Bobby Richardson 1959 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Only batting .232 through the season's first twenty games, he was benched after May 5 in favor of [[Tony Kubek]].<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=kubekto01&t=b&year=1959|title=Tony Kubek 1959 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill Dickey]], the [[hitting coach]] for the Yankees, worked with Richardson to improve his hitting. In 1959, Richardson switched to a heavier bat and tried swinging harder at pitches.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Given the chance to start at second base again in mid-June, Richardson raised his batting average from .232 to .300 over six games with 11 hits in 18 at bats.<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/> He reached the [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] and remained the starting second baseman the rest of the season.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/> On July 25, 1959, Richardson and [[Fritz Brickell]] both hit their first major league home runs, Richardson's coming against [[Paul Foytack]] in a 9\u20138 victory over the Tigers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/07/26/110087361.html?pageNumber=166|page=166|title=Homer Is Decisive|work=The New York Times|date=July 26, 1959|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Batting .298 coming into the final game of the year, Richardson was the only Yankee with a chance at hitting .300. Stengel promised to remove him from the game if he got a hit in his first at bat (moving his batting average to .300). Richardson flew out to [[Albie Pearson]] in his first at bat but got hits in his next two at bats to move his average to .301, then was pinch-hit for in the eighth, preserving the mark.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 134 games (469 at bats), he had 53 runs scored, 141 hits, 18 doubles, six triples, two home runs (both against Foytack), and 33 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"Shared Hero\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1960/10/09/99878556.html?pageNumber=276|page=276|title=Batting in 6 Runs, He Shares Role of Hero With Ford|work=The New York Times|date=October 9, 1960|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> His .301 average topped the Yankees and ranked sixth in the [[American League]] (AL),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1959-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1959 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> and he finished 18th in AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player (MVP)]] voting after the season.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIn 1960, Richardson remained the Yankees' starting second baseman all season.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1960|title=Bobby Richardson 1960 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> On April 30, June 30, and July 18, he had a season-high three hits.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\"/> One of those hits on April 30 was his only home run of the year, against [[Arnie Portocarrero]], in a 16\u20130 victory over the [[Baltimore Orioles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BAL/BAL196004300.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Baltimore Orioles Box Score, April 30, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> With the Yankees and Athletics tied 7\u20137 on May 6, Richardson singled against [[Bob Trowbridge]], stole second base, moved to third on a groundout by [[Ryne Duren]], then scored the winning run on a single by McDougald.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196005060.shtml|title=Kansas City Athletics at New York Yankees Box Score, May 6, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Batting .208 through June 17, he hit .370 from June 18 through July 23, raising his season average to .273. Thereafter, he batted .215 to finish the year with a .252 mark.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\"/> In 150 games (460 at bats), he had 45 runs scored, 116 hits, 12 doubles, three triples, and 26 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nThe Yankees faced the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] in the [[1960 World Series]]. Richardson went hitless in Game 1 but contributed three in Game 2, scoring three runs as well as the Yankees won 16\u20133.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> In Game 3, he came to bat in the first inning with the bases loaded against [[Clem Labine]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Terrell|first=Roy|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1960/10/17/the-knife-and-the-hammer|title=The Knife and the Hammer|work=Sports Illustrated|date=October 17, 1960|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Third base coach [[Frank Crosetti]] signaled him to [[Bunt (baseball)|bunt]], but after running the count to two strikes, Richardson cancelled the plan.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>{{efn|A bunt that goes [[Foul ball|foul]] with two strikes is considered the third strike to complete the strikeout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/07/case-play-2013-06-foul-bunt-with-two.html|title=Case Play 2013-06:Foul Bunt with Two Strikes (Completed)|date=10 July 2013|accessdate=28 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029021300/http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/07/case-play-2013-06-foul-bunt-with-two.html|archivedate=29 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>}} He remained at the plate long enough to run the at bat to a [[full count]], then hit a [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] to put the Yankees ahead 6\u20130. Up to bat with the bases loaded again in the fourth inning, he had a two-RBI single against [[Red Witt]]. His six RBI set a new record for most in a single World Series game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In Game 4, he had two hits and drove in another run, but the Yankees lost this one 3\u20132.<ref name=\"postseason Richardson\"/> After going hitless in Game 5, he hit two triples in Game 6, drove in three runs, and scored one in the Yankees' 12\u20130 rout of the Pirates to force Game 7.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"postseason Richardson\"/> He scored a run in the sixth inning, led off the ninth with a single against [[Harvey Haddix]], and scored another run, but New York lost the game 10\u20139.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PIT/PIT196010130.shtml|title=1960 World Series Game 7, Yankees at Pirates, October 13|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Though Pittsburgh second baseman [[Bill Mazeroski]] hit a [[walk-off home run]] in the bottom of the ninth to win the Series for Pittsburgh,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/world-series-history-bill-mazeroski-s-home-run-to-win-1960-world-series-100616|title=World Series History: Bill Mazeroski\u2019s Home Run to Win 1960 World Series|work=Fox Sports|date=June 30, 2017|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> it was Richardson who would be named the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP]] after hitting .367 with 12 RBI.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> He is the only World Series MVP who was playing for the losing team when he won the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://baseball-almanac.com/awards/aw_mvpw.shtml|title=World Series Most Valuable Player Award|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees gave him a new Corvette for his efforts.<ref name=\"Sunday Conversation\">{{cite web|last=Glover|first=Emery|url=https://thetandd.com/sports/t-d-sunday-conversation-with-bobby-richardson/article_378fc5f2-52ab-11e0-815b-001cc4c03286.html|title=T&D Sunday Conversation with...Bobby Richardson|work=The Times & Democrat|date=March 20, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Since he had a growing family, Richardson traded the car for a [[Chevrolet]] station wagon.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nHouk took over from Stengel as the Yankee manager in 1961; he inserted Richardson either first or second into the [[Batting order (baseball)|batting order]] each game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> On June 15, he had three hits and four RBI, including a three-run home run against [[Johnny Antonelli]] as the Yankees beat the [[Cleveland Indians]] 11\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|page=54|last=Drebinger|first=John|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1961/06/15/issue.html|title=Yankees Crush Indians|work=The New York Times|date=June 15, 1961|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> He had four RBI again in the second game of a doubleheader on July 9, including a three-run home run against [[Don Schwall]], but the Yankees lost that game 9\u20136 to the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196107092.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at New York Yankees Box Score, July 9, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Richardson won the [[List of Gold Glove Award winners at second base|Gold Glove at second base]], the first of five straight he would win at the position.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nHis best year was probably {{Baseball year|1962}}, when he batted .302 with 8 home runs and 59 runs batted in. His 209 hits led the [[American League]], and he stole 11 bases in 161 games. He made the AL [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] team, won his second Gold Glove, and came in second in the [[MLB Most Valuable Player Award|AL MVP]] voting, just behind teammate [[Mickey Mantle]]. \n\nHe also led the league in at bats three times, partly because he batted early in the order and partly because he rarely missed a game, coming to be known as a workhorse. His career high was 692 at bats in 161 games in 1962.\n\nDuring the 1963 season, Richardson's father suffered a stroke in May, then died on July 17. Richardson missed 11 games during the year visiting him and helping get his affairs in order.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Richardson's father\"/>\n\nThough he was just 31 following the 1966 season, Richardson retired following the year. He had made the decision the year before. \u201cI wanted to take the kids to school, help them with homework and watch or help coach their teams,\u201d he explained.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/> The Yankees honored him by declaring September 17 \"Bobby Richardson Day,\" making Richardson the tenth Yankee to be honored at the stadium with a special day. \u201cHow lucky it has been for me to have been a Yankee. To God be the glory,\" he addressed the fans.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/>\n\nHe had an all-time [[fielding percentage]] of .979 at second base, and six seasons with 100 or more double plays turned.\n\n===Postseason===\nRichardson won three [[World Series]] ([[1958 World Series|1958]], [[1961 World Series|1961]], [[1962 World Series|1962]]) of the seven he played with the Yankees ([[1957 World Series|1957]], 1958, [[1960 World Series|1960]], 1961, 1962, [[1963 World Series|1963]], [[1964 World Series|1964]]). In the 1962 World Series, he caught the final out of the 1962 Series; hardly moving from his position, he snared a screaming line drive off the bat of [[Willie McCovey]], which, if it had been two or three feet higher would have won the Series for the [[San Francisco Giants]].\n\n[[File:Bobby Richardson 1963.JPG|thumb|left|180px|Richardson in 1963.]]\nIn Game One of the [[1963 World Series]], which the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] swept in four games over the Yankees, Richardson struck out three times against [[Sandy Koufax]]\u2014his only three-strikeout game in 1,448 regular-season/World Series games. (Koufax would finish with 15 strikeouts, then a World Series single-game record.) Just that regular season, Richardson had struck out only 22 times in 630 at-bats, without ever striking out twice in one game.\n\nIn the [[1964 World Series]] against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], Richardson set a World Series record with 13 hits; this record has since been tied by [[Lou Brock]] and [[Marty Barrett (second baseman)|Marty Barrett]] in the [[1968 World Series|1968]] and [[1986 World Series]], respectively. However, batting against Cardinal ace [[Bob Gibson]] with the Yankees trailing 7\u20135 in the seventh and deciding game of that World Series, he popped out to [[Dal Maxvill]] for the final out of the Series. Richardson also had the dubious distinction of committing errors that affected the outcome of two games in the Series. In the sixth inning of Game Four, he mishandled [[Dick Groat]]'s ground ball for a double play that would have ended the inning with no runs scoring; the error was followed one batter later by [[Ken Boyer]]'s grand slam\u2014the four runs the Cardinals needed in defeating the Yankees 4\u20133. In the fifth inning of Game Five, he bobbled [[Curt Flood]]'s double play ground ball, which also would have ended that inning without any damage. The Cardinals eventually scored twice in the inning, then won the game 5\u20132 on [[Tim McCarver]]'s 10th inning, three-run home run.\n\n===Legacy===\nRichardson racked up 1,432 [[hit (baseball)|hits]] in his career, with a lifetime [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] of .266, 34 [[home run]]s and 390 [[run batted in|RBI]]s. Richardson's 12-year career statistics also include 643 [[run (baseball)|runs scored]] and 73 [[stolen base]]s. He also had 196 [[double (baseball)|double]]s and 37 [[triple (baseball)|triple]]s.\n\nRichardson won a [[List of Gold Glove Award winners at second base|Gold Glove at second base]] each year from 1961\u201365 (not until [[Robinson Can\u00f3]] in {{Baseball year|2010}} would another Yankee second baseman win a Gold Glove) while forming a top [[double play]] combination with [[shortstop]] and roommate [[Tony Kubek]]. With the light-hitting but superb-fielding Yankee [[third baseman]] [[Clete Boyer]], Richardson and Kubek gave the Yankees arguably the best defensive infield in baseball.<ref>{{cite web|last=Madden|first=Bill|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/clete-boyer-yanks-3rd-man-article-1.221914|title=Clete Boyer, Yanks' 3rd man|work=The New York Daily News|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Walker|first=Ben|agency=Associated Press|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/obituaries/articles/2007/06/05/clete_boyer_at_70_3d_baseman_for_yanks_was_brilliant_fielder/|title=Clete Boyer, at 70; 3d baseman for Yanks was brilliant fielder|work=boston.com|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> His most famous defensive play came at the end of the [[1962 World Series]], mentioned below, when Richardson made a clutch catch off a [[Willie McCovey]] line drive that prevented [[Willie Mays]] and [[Matty Alou]] from scoring the runs that would have beaten the Yankees and given the Series to the [[San Francisco Giants]].\n\nRichardson was also known for his ability to [[Contact hitter|make contact]]. He [[strikeout|struck out]] just 243 times in his entire 12-year career, less than 5% of his plate appearances.<ref name=\"reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/richabo01.shtml|title=Bobby Richardson Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> He was among the top three players in the league in [[at bat]]s per strikeout eight times during his career, and led the league three times, 1964\u20131966.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Richardson also led the league in sacrifice hits in 1962 and 1964.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Post professional baseball career===\nRichardson served as the head baseball coach for the [[South Carolina Gamecocks]] from 1970 to 1976. He would often pitch batting practice and drive the team bus for events. Richardson also tried to perform recruiting for the school but delegated the responsibility to others after he figured out \"I wasn't going after the good players.\"<ref name=\"finah\">{{cite web|last=Keith|first=Larry|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1975/06/02/nothin-could-be-finah|title=Nothin', could be finah|work=Sports Illustrated|date=June 2, 1975|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Under Richardson, Larry Keith of ''Sports Illustrated'' wrote, \"South Carolina rarely bunts, often hits-and-runs and is always looking for the big inning.\"<ref name=\"finah\"/> Richardson led the Gamecocks to their first NCAA Tournament appearance in 1974, which set the stage for what would happen a year later in 1975 when South Carolina posted a 51\u20136\u20131 record and made the College World Series for the first time ever.  They advanced all the way to the national championship game against Texas (a 5\u20131 Longhorns victory). Richardson left South Carolina after the 1976 season, finishing his tenure with a 221\u201392\u20131 record and three NCAA Tournament appearances.  Richardson is considered the father of Gamecocks baseball, and is credited with having set them on their path to becoming one of the elite college baseball programs in the NCAA still today. In the 1980s, Richardson served as the baseball coach for two seasons (1985\u201386) at [[Coastal Carolina University]] in [[Conway, South Carolina]], where he compiled a record of (61\u201338). After the 1986 season, he resigned as head coach at Coastal Carolina to replace [[Al Worthington]] as the baseball coach at [[Liberty University]]. \"I came here as athletic director under a different administration and [Chancellor] Ron [Eaglin] felt I should resign as athletic director and focus on baseball,\" Richardson explained the decision to resign, with Eaglin saying the two had disagreed on a budget for the next season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/10/sports/sports-people-richardson-moves-on.html?searchResultPosition=5|title=Sports People; Richardson Moves On|work=The New York Times|page=D-31|date=April 10, 1986|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Nixon tried to convince Richardson to run for the [[United States Congress]]in [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district]]. Later, a private poll indicated he was the favorite.<ref name=\"finah\"/> Two years later, he did run for the seat as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], losing to incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Kenneth Lamar Holland|Kenneth Holland]] by a narrow margin. Holland was aided by the strength of [[Jimmy Carter]]'s winning campaign in South Carolina to hold off Richardson by a tally of 66,073 (51.4%) to 62,095 (48.3%). His campaign was supported by former baseball players [[Joe DiMaggio]], [[Ted Williams]], [[Bob Feller]], and [[Wilmer Mizell|Wilmer \"Vinegar Bend\" Mizell]] among others.  Richardson's old friend, Yankee shortstop [[Tony Kubek]], declined to campaign for him because Kubek was a Democrat.<ref>{{cite book |title=October 1964 |last= Halberstam |first=David |authorlink= |year=1995 |publisher=Random House Digital, Inc. |location= |isbn= 0-449-98367-6 |pages=366\u2013367 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sZ7sUkp5eBcC&lpg=PP1&dq=october%201964&pg=PA366#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref>\n\nRichardson is a [[born-again Christian]]. During his time with the Yankees, he would organize church services for the team when they were travelling. Friend and teammate [[Mickey Mantle]] described him as a \"clean-living, practicing Christian.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Mantle|first=Mickey|title=The Mick|location=New York|publisher=Jove Books|year=1985|page=220|isbn=978-0385194563}}</ref> He was involved with the [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]] (FCA) and the [[American Tract Society]] (ATS) during his career, as well as many charities.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> After his career, he continued to be involved with those organizations. He served as the president of the Baseball Chapel for 10 years, served on the President's Council for Physical Fitness, and earned the Golden Gavel Award from [[Toastmasters International]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> President [[Richard Nixon]], who hosted church services at the [[White House]] each week of his presidency, invited the FCA to speak on October 18, 1970. One of four representatives, Richardson spoke on [[Jesus and the rich young man]] from [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]], Chapter 10. Concerning the young man's search for guidance, Richardson said, \"He didn't go to India and ask a guru; he didn't get caught up in the younger generation, but he went to God's son, Jesus Christ, the Messiah, with his question.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last=Fiske|first=Edward B.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/08/08/archives/praying-with-the-president-in-the-white-house-praying-with-the.html|page=SM-14|title=Praying With the President In the White House|work=The New York Times|date=August 8, 1971|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> He has spoken at five [[Billy Graham Crusade]]s, as well as at various churches.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/> Today, he is a speaker with Christian Speakers 360, available to appear at events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/bobby-richardson.php|title=Bobby Richardson Speaker Information|work=Christian Speakers 360|accessdate=April 16, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813113113/http://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/bobby-richardson.php|archivedate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRichardson also officiated at Mantle's funeral.\n\nHis 2012 book, ''Impact Player'' chronicles his life including his years with the Yankee dynasty.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn the late 1960s, an LP record (LP # W-3343-LP) titled ''The Bobby Richardson Story'' was released. The sub-title is \"The Exciting First-Person Account of His Own Life, By the Yankees' Famous Second Baseman\". In 1965, Bobby wrote his own biography, \"The Bobby Richardson Story.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Richardson|first1=Bobby|title=The Bobby Richardson Story|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17332889-the-bobby-richardson-story|website=Goodreads}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRichardson met Betsy Dobson at Grace Baptist Church of Sumter.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\">{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Rudy|url=https://baptistcourier.com/2016/07/christian-faith-marks-yankee-legend-bobby-richardsons-career-home-life/|title=Christian faith marks Yankee legend Bobby Richardson\u2019s career, home life|work=Baptist Courier|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> In 1954, they went to a [[miniature golf]] course on their first date. Two years later, they were married. In an unusual move, Houk granted Richardson permission to leave the Denver Bears midseason to get married.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> The couple had three sons\u2013Robbie (born 7/2/57), Ron (7/13/58), and Rich (8/27/68)\u2013and two daughters\u2013Christie (12/30/60) and Jeannie (1/21/64).<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 1960, the Richardsons were renting a house in [[Ridgewood, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> They lived Sumter during offseasons, where Richardson was a general secretary for the local [[Young Men's Christian Association]] and host for a radio sports show.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> Hunting is one of his favorite hobbies.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> He and Shantz went gun-shopping together in Kansas City in 1959,<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> and fellow major-leaguer [[Billy O'Dell]] used to hunt with him in the offseason.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His roommates when travelling with the Yankees at various times included Kubek and [[Bobby Shantz]].<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Major League Baseball players who spent their entire career with one franchise]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=121161|espn=26747|br=r/richabo01|fangraphs=1010903|brm=richar007rob}}\n\n{{1958 New York Yankees}}\n{{1961 New York Yankees}}\n{{1962 New York Yankees}}\n{{World Series MVPs}}\n{{Lou Gehrig Memorial Award}}\n{{AL 2B Gold Glove Award}}\n{{South Carolina Gamecocks head baseball coaches}}\n{{Liberty Flames baseball coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball second basemen]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees scouts]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Olean Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Fellowship of Christian Athletes]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Liberty Flames baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Coastal Carolina Chanticleers baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:American athlete-politicians]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sumter, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:World Series Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{about|the baseball player|the football player|Bobby Richardson (American football)|the North Carolina politician|Bobbie Richardson}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Bobby Richardson\n|image=Bobby Richardson - New York Yankees.jpg\n|caption=Richardson, circa 1964\u201366\n|position=[[Second baseman]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1935|8|19}}\n|birth_place=[[Sumter, South Carolina]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=August 5\n|debutyear=1955\n|debutteam=New York Yankees\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 2\n|finalyear=1966\n|finalteam=New York Yankees\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.266\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=34\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=390\n|teams=\n* [[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|1955}}\u2013{{mlby|1966}})\n|highlights=\n* 8\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1957 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1957]], [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1959\u00b2]], [[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1962]]\u2013[[1966 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1966]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1958}}, {{wsy|1961}}, {{wsy|1962}})\n* [[World Series MVP]] (1960)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (1961\u20131965)\n}}\n'''Robert Clinton Richardson, Jr.''' (born August 19, 1935) is a former [[second baseman]] in [[Major League Baseball]] who played for the [[New York Yankees]] from {{Baseball year|1955}} through {{Baseball year|1966}}. Batting and throwing right-handed, he was a superb defensive infielder, as well as something of a clutch hitter, who played a large role in the Yankee baseball dynasty of his day. He is the only [[World Series MVP Award|World Series MVP]] ever to be selected from the losing team. He wore the uniform number 1 for the majority of his career (1958\u20131966).\n\n==Early life==\nRichardson was the middle child of Robert Sr. and Debbie Richardson of [[Sumter, South Carolina]]. He had two sisters, Inez (older) and Willie Ann (younger).<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Richardson Marble and Granite Works in Sumter was managed by Robert Sr., who also owned some of the interest in the company.<ref name=\"Richardson's father\">{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1963/06/18/80711961.html?pageNumber=37|title=Bobby Richardson's Father, 57|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 1963|accessdate=April 10, 2020|page=37}}</ref>\n\nGrowing up, Richardson practiced his baseball skills with Harry Stokes, a boy in his neighborhood seven years his senior who would play catch with him. Richardson played on a local [[YMCA]]/[[Salvation Army]] team at the age of ten. Later, he played on ballclubs sponsored by the local [[Kiwanis Club]] and [[American Legion]]. On the American Legion team, Richardson's coach was [[Fred Hutchinson]], who would later manage the [[Cincinnati Reds]] when Richardson faced them in the [[1961 World Series]]. Hutchinson and Richardson became American Legion champions in 1952, Richardson's junior year of high school. Hutchinson also coached Richardson at Edmunds High School.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n11 out of 16 [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) teams showed interest in Richardson, as well as the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] and [[Georgia Tech University]], which offered baseball scholarships. [[Mayo Smith]], manager of the [[Norfolk Tars]], a team in the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Piedmont League]] and an affiliate of the [[New York Yankees]], scouted Richardson for New York, as did Bill Harris. Ultimately, Richardson decided to forgo college and sign with the Yankees out of high school (though he later earned a degree in accounting).<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Sunday Conversation\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nRichardson started his [[Minor league baseball|minor league]] career in 1953 with the [[Norfolk Tars]] of the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Piedmont League]], travelling by bus to Norfolk from Sumter with $85 in coins friends and family had given him.<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web|last=Pasculli|first=Len|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/47363efd|title=Bobby Richardson|work=SABR|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> After Richardson [[Batting average|batted]] just .211 in his first 27 games with the Tars, the Yankees assigned him to a [[Class D (baseball)|Class D]] team, the [[Olean Yankees]] of the [[New York\u2013Penn League|PONY League]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"minors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=richar007rob|title=Bobby Richardson Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> With Olean, he batted .412 in 32 games and hit his first [[home run]].<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nIn 1954, Richardson was promoted, heading up to the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[Binghamton Triplets]] of the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] without having to return to Norfolk. Spending the whole year in Binghamton, he ranked among the Eastern League leaders in games (141, tied for first), [[Runs scored|runs]] (81, fifth), 171 [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] (first), [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (29, second to Clyde Parris's 40), and batting average (.310, second to Parris's .313).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=af825f91|title=1954 Eastern League Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> For his contributions, Richardson was named the Eastern League's [[Most Valuable Player]] (MVP).<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nRichardson spent most of [[spring training]] with the Yankees in 1955 but was sent to the [[Class AAA (baseball)|Class AAA]] [[Denver Bears]] of the [[American Association (20th Century)|American Assocation]] to start the year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=31|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1955/04/01/85690101.html?pageNumber=31|title=Five Players Cut From Squad Before Yanks Start Northward|work=The New York Times|date=April 1, 1955|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> In 119 games with the Bears, he batted .296 with 146 hits, 99 runs scord, 21 doubles, 12 [[Triple (baseball)|triples]], six home runs, and 59 RBI.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nWhen [[Gil McDougald]] found himself on the receiving end of a [[line drive]] during [[batting practice]] in August of 1955, the Yankees called up Richardson.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He debuted on August 5, 1955, getting his first hit against [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Jim Bunning]] in a 3\u20130 victory over the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In the field, he was a \"nervous wreck\" as he later described, but no balls were hit to him.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bobby Richardson Story|first=Bobby |last=Richardson |location=Old Tappan, New Jersey|publisher=Fleming H. Revell Co.|year=1965|page=84}}</ref> He started four games at second base in three days (including an August 7 [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]]), then entered three games in the late innings at [[shortstop]] before getting sent to the minor leagues on August 15 to make room for a [[pitcher]] returning from the [[disabled list]].<ref name=\"1955 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Drebinger|first=John|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1955/08/16/79451253.html?pageNumber=26|title=Home Runs Mark 5\u20134, 12\u20136 Triumphs|work=The New York Times|date=August 16, 1955|accessdate=April 10, 2020|page=26}}</ref> For some reason, he was sent to the [[Richmond Virginians]] of the Class AAA [[International League]] this time, with whom he finished the season.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Called up again in [[September call-up|September]], he appeared in four more games for the Yankees before the end of the year.<ref name=\"1955 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1955|title=Bobby Richardson 1955 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, Richardson started the season with the Yankees. However, he only appeared in five games for them, batting .143 before getting sent back to Denver May 13.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=42|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/05/14/93203323.html?pageNumber=42|title=Bombers Win, 11\u20132; Drop 5\u20131 Decision|work=The New York Times|date=May 14, 1956|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> With the Bears, he ranked among the American Association leaders in batting average (.328, third), runs scored (102, sixth), hits (175, fourth), doubles (30, ninth), and triples (12, tied with [[Willie Kirkland]] for second behind [[Larry Raines]]'s 14).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=62cbeec8|title=1956 American Association Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRichardson made the team in 1957 and took over the second base job from [[Billy Martin]], the Yankees' volatile infielder who injured himself in a deliberate golf cart collision with [[Mickey Mantle]] in spring training, then got into a highly-publicized brawl at the [[Copacabana (nightclub)|Copacabana Club]] in May before getting traded to the [[Kansas City Athletics]] in June.<ref name=\"Silence\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=34|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/06/25/84738480.html?pageNumber=34|title=Silence! Bobby Richardson at Work|work=The New York Times|date=June 25, 1957|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Golenbock|first=Peter|origyear=1994|title=Wild, High and Tight: The Life and Death of Billy Martin|publisher=Antenna Books|edition=Kindle version of Antenna Books ebook |page=2631\u20132644 |location=New York|year=2014|isbn=978-1-62306-022-0|ref={{sfnRef|Golenbock}}}}</ref> Richardson proved a quieter sort of character, if not a great hitter in 1957; manager [[Casey Stengel]] said, \"Look at him. He doesn't drink, he doesn't smoke, he doesn't chew, he doesn't stay out late, and he still can't hit .250.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His fielding was better; [[Louis Effrat]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote June 25, \"He has thrilled the fans with his great stops and catches...no one gets rid of the ball quicker [on [[double play]]s].\"<ref name=\"Silence\"/> Actually, Richardson's .331 average trailed only Mantle among the Yankees on June 25,<ref name=\"Silence\"/> and he made his first appearance in the [[1957 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] that year.<ref name=\"reference\"/> However, he batted .188 over the rest of the year, finishing the season with a .256 mark and 78 hits in 305 [[at bat]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1957|title=Bobby Richardson 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy September, Richardson was losing a lot of starts to [[Jerry Coleman]] at second base.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=colemje01&t=b&year=1957|title=Jerry Coleman 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Even so, Stengel waited until the last minute to decide whether Coleman or Richardson would start at second base in the [[1957 World Series]] against the [[Milwaukee Braves]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/10/01/91165032.html?pageNumber=54|title=Mantle's Status Remains in Doubt|work=The New York Times|date=October 1, 1957|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Ultimately, Stengel chose Coleman, who started all seven games for the Yankees as Richardson was limited to two appearances as a [[pinch-runner]] and [[defensive replacement]].<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Coleman\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=colemje01&t=b&year=0&post=1|title=Jerry Coleman Postseason Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees lost the Series in seven games.<ref name=\"Postseason Coleman\"/>\n\nColeman retired following the 1957 season, and Richardson began 1958 as the Yankees' starting second baseman.<ref>{{cite web|last=McGowen|first=Roscoe|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/11/22/90856130.html?pageNumber=38|page=38|title=Coleman Retires as Player After Nine Years with Yankees|work=The New York Times|date=November 22, 1957|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> After batting .203 through the Yankees' first 18 games, he missed 20 in a row as McDougald began getting the starts at second.<ref name=\"1958 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1958|title=Bobby Richardson 1958 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mcdougi01&t=b&year=1958|title=Gil McDougald 1958 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Richardson started at second from June 5 through June 12 but thereafter spent most of the season on the bench until September, when he again got a few starts at second base.<ref name=\"1958 Richardson\"/> In 73 games (182 at bats), he batted .247 with 18 runs scored and 45 hits.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Richardson considered quitting baseball that season because of his struggles, but [[Ralph Houk]], the Yankees' [[General manager (baseball)|general manager]] and Richardson's former manager at Denver, convinced him to keep playing.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In the [[1958 World Series]], again against the Braves, Richardson finished three games for the Yankees at [[third base]] and also started Game 4 at third, though he was hitless in two at bats before getting pinch-hit for in the seventh by [[Elston Howard]].<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=0&post=1|title=Bobby Richardson Postseason Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA195810050.shtml|title=1958 World Series Game 4, Braves at Yankees, October 5|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> However, he became a World Series champion for the first time as this year, the Yankees defeated the Braves in seven games.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nRichardson began 1959 as the Yankees' shortstop; Effrat wrote, \"[Richardson] is a tremendous fielder no matter where [the Yankees] play him.\"<ref name=\"Kiely\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/04/20/89183045.html?pageNumber=37|title=Kiely Is Credited with 5\u20134 Victory|work=The New York Times|page=37|date=April 20, 1959|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He moved to second base on April 18 after McDougald suffered cracked knuckles, then returned to shortstop on April 29 when McDougald returned to the lineup.<ref name=\"Kiely\"/><ref name=\"1959 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1959|title=Bobby Richardson 1959 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Only batting .232 through the season's first twenty games, he was benched after May 5 in favor of [[Tony Kubek]].<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=kubekto01&t=b&year=1959|title=Tony Kubek 1959 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill Dickey]], the [[hitting coach]] for the Yankees, worked with Richardson to improve his hitting. In 1959, Richardson switched to a heavier bat and tried swinging harder at pitches.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Given the chance to start at second base again in mid-June, Richardson raised his batting average from .232 to .300 over six games with 11 hits in 18 at bats.<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/> He reached the [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] and remained the starting second baseman the rest of the season.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/> On July 25, 1959, Richardson and [[Fritz Brickell]] both hit their first major league home runs, Richardson's coming against [[Paul Foytack]] in a 9\u20138 victory over the Tigers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/07/26/110087361.html?pageNumber=166|page=166|title=Homer Is Decisive|work=The New York Times|date=July 26, 1959|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Batting .298 coming into the final game of the year, Richardson was the only Yankee with a chance at hitting .300. Stengel promised to remove him from the game if he got a hit in his first at bat (moving his batting average to .300). Richardson flew out to [[Albie Pearson]] in his first at bat but got hits in his next two at bats to move his average to .301, then was pinch-hit for in the eighth, preserving the mark.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 134 games (469 at bats), he had 53 runs scored, 141 hits, 18 doubles, six triples, two home runs (both against Foytack), and 33 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"Shared Hero\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1960/10/09/99878556.html?pageNumber=276|page=276|title=Batting in 6 Runs, He Shares Role of Hero With Ford|work=The New York Times|date=October 9, 1960|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> His .301 average topped the Yankees and ranked sixth in the [[American League]] (AL),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1959-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1959 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> and he finished 18th in AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player (MVP)]] voting after the season.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIn 1960, Richardson remained the Yankees' starting second baseman all season.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1960|title=Bobby Richardson 1960 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> On April 30, June 30, and July 18, he had a season-high three hits.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\"/> One of those hits on April 30 was his only home run of the year, against [[Arnie Portocarrero]], in a 16\u20130 victory over the [[Baltimore Orioles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BAL/BAL196004300.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Baltimore Orioles Box Score, April 30, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> With the Yankees and Athletics tied 7\u20137 on May 6, Richardson singled against [[Bob Trowbridge]], stole second base, moved to third on a groundout by [[Ryne Duren]], then scored the winning run on a single by McDougald.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196005060.shtml|title=Kansas City Athletics at New York Yankees Box Score, May 6, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Batting .208 through June 17, he hit .370 from June 18 through July 23, raising his season average to .273. Thereafter, he batted .215 to finish the year with a .252 mark.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\"/> In 150 games (460 at bats), he had 45 runs scored, 116 hits, 12 doubles, three triples, and 26 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nThe Yankees faced the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] in the [[1960 World Series]]. Richardson went hitless in Game 1 but contributed three in Game 2, scoring three runs as well as the Yankees won 16\u20133.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> In Game 3, he came to bat in the first inning with the bases loaded against [[Clem Labine]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Terrell|first=Roy|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1960/10/17/the-knife-and-the-hammer|title=The Knife and the Hammer|work=Sports Illustrated|date=October 17, 1960|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Third base coach [[Frank Crosetti]] signaled him to [[Bunt (baseball)|bunt]], but after running the count to two strikes, Richardson cancelled the plan.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>{{efn|A bunt that goes [[Foul ball|foul]] with two strikes is considered the third strike to complete the strikeout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/07/case-play-2013-06-foul-bunt-with-two.html|title=Case Play 2013-06:Foul Bunt with Two Strikes (Completed)|date=10 July 2013|accessdate=28 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029021300/http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/07/case-play-2013-06-foul-bunt-with-two.html|archivedate=29 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>}} He remained at the plate long enough to run the at bat to a [[full count]], then hit a [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] to put the Yankees ahead 6\u20130. Up to bat with the bases loaded again in the fourth inning, he had a two-RBI single against [[Red Witt]]. His six RBI set a new record for most in a single World Series game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In Game 4, he had two hits and drove in another run, but the Yankees lost this one 3\u20132.<ref name=\"postseason Richardson\"/> After going hitless in Game 5, he hit two triples in Game 6, drove in three runs, and scored one in the Yankees' 12\u20130 rout of the Pirates to force Game 7.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"postseason Richardson\"/> He scored a run in the sixth inning, led off the ninth with a single against [[Harvey Haddix]], and scored another run, but New York lost the game 10\u20139.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PIT/PIT196010130.shtml|title=1960 World Series Game 7, Yankees at Pirates, October 13|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Though Pittsburgh second baseman [[Bill Mazeroski]] hit a [[walk-off home run]] in the bottom of the ninth to win the Series for Pittsburgh,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/world-series-history-bill-mazeroski-s-home-run-to-win-1960-world-series-100616|title=World Series History: Bill Mazeroski\u2019s Home Run to Win 1960 World Series|work=Fox Sports|date=June 30, 2017|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> it was Richardson who would be named the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP]] after hitting .367 with 12 RBI.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> He is the only World Series MVP who was playing for the losing team when he won the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://baseball-almanac.com/awards/aw_mvpw.shtml|title=World Series Most Valuable Player Award|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees gave him a new Corvette for his efforts.<ref name=\"Sunday Conversation\">{{cite web|last=Glover|first=Emery|url=https://thetandd.com/sports/t-d-sunday-conversation-with-bobby-richardson/article_378fc5f2-52ab-11e0-815b-001cc4c03286.html|title=T&D Sunday Conversation with...Bobby Richardson|work=The Times & Democrat|date=March 20, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Since he had a growing family, Richardson traded the car for a [[Chevrolet]] station wagon.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nHouk took over from Stengel as the Yankee manager in 1961; he inserted Richardson either first or second into the [[Batting order (baseball)|batting order]] each game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> On June 15, he had three hits and four RBI, including a three-run home run against [[Johnny Antonelli]] as the Yankees beat the [[Cleveland Indians]] 11\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|page=54|last=Drebinger|first=John|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1961/06/15/issue.html|title=Yankees Crush Indians|work=The New York Times|date=June 15, 1961|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> He had four RBI again in the second game of a doubleheader on June 9, including a three-run home run against [[Don Schwall]], but the Yankees lost that game 9\u20136 to the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196107092.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at New York Yankees Box Score, July 9, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Richardson won the [[List of Gold Glove Award winners at second base|Gold Glove at second base]], the first of five straight he would win at the position.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nHis best year was probably {{Baseball year|1962}}, when he batted .302 with 8 home runs and 59 runs batted in. His 209 hits led the [[American League]], and he stole 11 bases in 161 games. He made the AL [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] team, won his second Gold Glove, and came in second in the [[MLB Most Valuable Player Award|AL MVP]] voting, just behind teammate [[Mickey Mantle]]. \n\nHe also led the league in at bats three times, partly because he batted early in the order and partly because he rarely missed a game, coming to be known as a workhorse. His career high was 692 at bats in 161 games in 1962.\n\nDuring the 1963 season, Richardson's father suffered a stroke in May, then died on July 17. Richardson missed 11 games during the year visiting him and helping get his affairs in order.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Richardson's father\"/>\n\nThough he was just 31 following the 1966 season, Richardson retired following the year. He had made the decision the year before. \u201cI wanted to take the kids to school, help them with homework and watch or help coach their teams,\u201d he explained.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/> The Yankees honored him by declaring September 17 \"Bobby Richardson Day,\" making Richardson the tenth Yankee to be honored at the stadium with a special day. \u201cHow lucky it has been for me to have been a Yankee. To God be the glory,\" he addressed the fans.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/>\n\nHe had an all-time [[fielding percentage]] of .979 at second base, and six seasons with 100 or more double plays turned.\n\n===Postseason===\nRichardson won three [[World Series]] ([[1958 World Series|1958]], [[1961 World Series|1961]], [[1962 World Series|1962]]) of the seven he played with the Yankees ([[1957 World Series|1957]], 1958, [[1960 World Series|1960]], 1961, 1962, [[1963 World Series|1963]], [[1964 World Series|1964]]). In the 1962 World Series, he caught the final out of the 1962 Series; hardly moving from his position, he snared a screaming line drive off the bat of [[Willie McCovey]], which, if it had been two or three feet higher would have won the Series for the [[San Francisco Giants]].\n\n[[File:Bobby Richardson 1963.JPG|thumb|left|180px|Richardson in 1963.]]\nIn Game One of the [[1963 World Series]], which the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] swept in four games over the Yankees, Richardson struck out three times against [[Sandy Koufax]]\u2014his only three-strikeout game in 1,448 regular-season/World Series games. (Koufax would finish with 15 strikeouts, then a World Series single-game record.) Just that regular season, Richardson had struck out only 22 times in 630 at-bats, without ever striking out twice in one game.\n\nIn the [[1964 World Series]] against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], Richardson set a World Series record with 13 hits; this record has since been tied by [[Lou Brock]] and [[Marty Barrett (second baseman)|Marty Barrett]] in the [[1968 World Series|1968]] and [[1986 World Series]], respectively. However, batting against Cardinal ace [[Bob Gibson]] with the Yankees trailing 7\u20135 in the seventh and deciding game of that World Series, he popped out to [[Dal Maxvill]] for the final out of the Series. Richardson also had the dubious distinction of committing errors that affected the outcome of two games in the Series. In the sixth inning of Game Four, he mishandled [[Dick Groat]]'s ground ball for a double play that would have ended the inning with no runs scoring; the error was followed one batter later by [[Ken Boyer]]'s grand slam\u2014the four runs the Cardinals needed in defeating the Yankees 4\u20133. In the fifth inning of Game Five, he bobbled [[Curt Flood]]'s double play ground ball, which also would have ended that inning without any damage. The Cardinals eventually scored twice in the inning, then won the game 5\u20132 on [[Tim McCarver]]'s 10th inning, three-run home run.\n\n===Legacy===\nRichardson racked up 1,432 [[hit (baseball)|hits]] in his career, with a lifetime [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] of .266, 34 [[home run]]s and 390 [[run batted in|RBI]]s. Richardson's 12-year career statistics also include 643 [[run (baseball)|runs scored]] and 73 [[stolen base]]s. He also had 196 [[double (baseball)|double]]s and 37 [[triple (baseball)|triple]]s.\n\nRichardson won a [[List of Gold Glove Award winners at second base|Gold Glove at second base]] each year from 1961\u201365 (not until [[Robinson Can\u00f3]] in {{Baseball year|2010}} would another Yankee second baseman win a Gold Glove) while forming a top [[double play]] combination with [[shortstop]] and roommate [[Tony Kubek]]. With the light-hitting but superb-fielding Yankee [[third baseman]] [[Clete Boyer]], Richardson and Kubek gave the Yankees arguably the best defensive infield in baseball.<ref>{{cite web|last=Madden|first=Bill|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/clete-boyer-yanks-3rd-man-article-1.221914|title=Clete Boyer, Yanks' 3rd man|work=The New York Daily News|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Walker|first=Ben|agency=Associated Press|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/obituaries/articles/2007/06/05/clete_boyer_at_70_3d_baseman_for_yanks_was_brilliant_fielder/|title=Clete Boyer, at 70; 3d baseman for Yanks was brilliant fielder|work=boston.com|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> His most famous defensive play came at the end of the [[1962 World Series]], mentioned below, when Richardson made a clutch catch off a [[Willie McCovey]] line drive that prevented [[Willie Mays]] and [[Matty Alou]] from scoring the runs that would have beaten the Yankees and given the Series to the [[San Francisco Giants]].\n\nRichardson was also known for his ability to [[Contact hitter|make contact]]. He [[strikeout|struck out]] just 243 times in his entire 12-year career, less than 5% of his plate appearances.<ref name=\"reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/richabo01.shtml|title=Bobby Richardson Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> He was among the top three players in the league in [[at bat]]s per strikeout eight times during his career, and led the league three times, 1964\u20131966.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Richardson also led the league in sacrifice hits in 1962 and 1964.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Post professional baseball career===\nRichardson served as the head baseball coach for the [[South Carolina Gamecocks]] from 1970 to 1976. He would often pitch batting practice and drive the team bus for events. Richardson also tried to perform recruiting for the school but delegated the responsibility to others after he figured out \"I wasn't going after the good players.\"<ref name=\"finah\">{{cite web|last=Keith|first=Larry|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1975/06/02/nothin-could-be-finah|title=Nothin', could be finah|work=Sports Illustrated|date=June 2, 1975|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Under Richardson, Larry Keith of ''Sports Illustrated'' wrote, \"South Carolina rarely bunts, often hits-and-runs and is always looking for the big inning.\"<ref name=\"finah\"/> Richardson led the Gamecocks to their first NCAA Tournament appearance in 1974, which set the stage for what would happen a year later in 1975 when South Carolina posted a 51\u20136\u20131 record and made the College World Series for the first time ever.  They advanced all the way to the national championship game against Texas (a 5\u20131 Longhorns victory). Richardson left South Carolina after the 1976 season, finishing his tenure with a 221\u201392\u20131 record and three NCAA Tournament appearances.  Richardson is considered the father of Gamecocks baseball, and is credited with having set them on their path to becoming one of the elite college baseball programs in the NCAA still today. In the 1980s, Richardson served as the baseball coach for two seasons (1985\u201386) at [[Coastal Carolina University]] in [[Conway, South Carolina]], where he compiled a record of (61\u201338). After the 1986 season, he resigned as head coach at Coastal Carolina to replace [[Al Worthington]] as the baseball coach at [[Liberty University]]. \"I came here as athletic director under a different administration and [Chancellor] Ron [Eaglin] felt I should resign as athletic director and focus on baseball,\" Richardson explained the decision to resign, with Eaglin saying the two had disagreed on a budget for the next season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/10/sports/sports-people-richardson-moves-on.html?searchResultPosition=5|title=Sports People; Richardson Moves On|work=The New York Times|page=D-31|date=April 10, 1986|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Nixon tried to convince Richardson to run for the [[United States Congress]]in [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district]]. Later, a private poll indicated he was the favorite.<ref name=\"finah\"/> Two years later, he did run for the seat as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], losing to incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Kenneth Lamar Holland|Kenneth Holland]] by a narrow margin. Holland was aided by the strength of [[Jimmy Carter]]'s winning campaign in South Carolina to hold off Richardson by a tally of 66,073 (51.4%) to 62,095 (48.3%). His campaign was supported by former baseball players [[Joe DiMaggio]], [[Ted Williams]], [[Bob Feller]], and [[Wilmer Mizell|Wilmer \"Vinegar Bend\" Mizell]] among others.  Richardson's old friend, Yankee shortstop [[Tony Kubek]], declined to campaign for him because Kubek was a Democrat.<ref>{{cite book |title=October 1964 |last= Halberstam |first=David |authorlink= |year=1995 |publisher=Random House Digital, Inc. |location= |isbn= 0-449-98367-6 |pages=366\u2013367 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sZ7sUkp5eBcC&lpg=PP1&dq=october%201964&pg=PA366#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref>\n\nRichardson is a [[born-again Christian]]. During his time with the Yankees, he would organize church services for the team when they were travelling. Friend and teammate [[Mickey Mantle]] described him as a \"clean-living, practicing Christian.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Mantle|first=Mickey|title=The Mick|location=New York|publisher=Jove Books|year=1985|page=220|isbn=978-0385194563}}</ref> He was involved with the [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]] (FCA) and the [[American Tract Society]] (ATS) during his career, as well as many charities.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> After his career, he continued to be involved with those organizations. He served as the president of the Baseball Chapel for 10 years, served on the President's Council for Physical Fitness, and earned the Golden Gavel Award from [[Toastmasters International]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> President [[Richard Nixon]], who hosted church services at the [[White House]] each week of his presidency, invited the FCA to speak on October 18, 1970. One of four representatives, Richardson spoke on [[Jesus and the rich young man]] from [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]], Chapter 10. Concerning the young man's search for guidance, Richardson said, \"He didn't go to India and ask a guru; he didn't get caught up in the younger generation, but he went to God's son, Jesus Christ, the Messiah, with his question.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last=Fiske|first=Edward B.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/08/08/archives/praying-with-the-president-in-the-white-house-praying-with-the.html|page=SM-14|title=Praying With the President In the White House|work=The New York Times|date=August 8, 1971|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> He has spoken at five [[Billy Graham Crusade]]s, as well as at various churches.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/> Today, he is a speaker with Christian Speakers 360, available to appear at events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/bobby-richardson.php|title=Bobby Richardson Speaker Information|work=Christian Speakers 360|accessdate=April 16, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813113113/http://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/bobby-richardson.php|archivedate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRichardson also officiated at Mantle's funeral.\n\nHis 2012 book, ''Impact Player'' chronicles his life including his years with the Yankee dynasty.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn the late 1960s, an LP record (LP # W-3343-LP) titled ''The Bobby Richardson Story'' was released. The sub-title is \"The Exciting First-Person Account of His Own Life, By the Yankees' Famous Second Baseman\". In 1965, Bobby wrote his own biography, \"The Bobby Richardson Story.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Richardson|first1=Bobby|title=The Bobby Richardson Story|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17332889-the-bobby-richardson-story|website=Goodreads}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRichardson met Betsy Dobson at Grace Baptist Church of Sumter.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\">{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Rudy|url=https://baptistcourier.com/2016/07/christian-faith-marks-yankee-legend-bobby-richardsons-career-home-life/|title=Christian faith marks Yankee legend Bobby Richardson\u2019s career, home life|work=Baptist Courier|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> In 1954, they went to a [[miniature golf]] course on their first date. Two years later, they were married. In an unusual move, Houk granted Richardson permission to leave the Denver Bears midseason to get married.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> The couple had three sons\u2013Robbie (born 7/2/57), Ron (7/13/58), and Rich (8/27/68)\u2013and two daughters\u2013Christie (12/30/60) and Jeannie (1/21/64).<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 1960, the Richardsons were renting a house in [[Ridgewood, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> They lived Sumter during offseasons, where Richardson was a general secretary for the local [[Young Men's Christian Association]] and host for a radio sports show.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> Hunting is one of his favorite hobbies.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> He and Shantz went gun-shopping together in Kansas City in 1959,<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> and fellow major-leaguer [[Billy O'Dell]] used to hunt with him in the offseason.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His roommates when travelling with the Yankees at various times included Kubek and [[Bobby Shantz]].<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Major League Baseball players who spent their entire career with one franchise]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=121161|espn=26747|br=r/richabo01|fangraphs=1010903|brm=richar007rob}}\n\n{{1958 New York Yankees}}\n{{1961 New York Yankees}}\n{{1962 New York Yankees}}\n{{World Series MVPs}}\n{{Lou Gehrig Memorial Award}}\n{{AL 2B Gold Glove Award}}\n{{South Carolina Gamecocks head baseball coaches}}\n{{Liberty Flames baseball coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball second basemen]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees scouts]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Olean Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Fellowship of Christian Athletes]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Liberty Flames baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Coastal Carolina Chanticleers baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:American athlete-politicians]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sumter, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:World Series Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Sanfranciscogiants17", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobby_Richardson"}
{"title_page": "Mahunwal", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{use Indian English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Mahunwal\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = Village \n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Punjab#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Punjab, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|31.110952|N|75.488333|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Jalandhar district|Jalandhar]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| parts_type              = [[Taluka]]s\n| parts                   = [[Nakodar tehsil|Nakodar]]\n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Gurmukhi|Punjabi]]\n| demographics1_title2    = Regional\n| demographics1_info2     = [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 0181\n| registration_plate      = [[List of RTO districts in India#PB.E2.80.94Punjab|PB]]- 08 \n| blank1_name_sec1        = Nearest city\n| blank1_info_sec1        = [[Nurmahal]]\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Mahunwal''' is a small village in [[Nakodar]].  Nakodar is a [[tehsil]] in the city of [[Jalandhar]] in the Indian state of [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]].\n\n== About ==\nThe nearest main road to Mahunwal is [[Nakodar]]-[[Nurmahal]] road which is almost half a km from the village. The nearest Railway station to this village is Nakodar Railway station. Mahunwal's STD code is 01821.\n[[File:Mahunwal.jpg|thumb|250 px|left|A way marker marking the limits of the village]]\n[[File:A distant view of Mahunwal.jpg|thumb|250 px|left|A distant view of Mahunwal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://www.mypind.com/jal/jalPage531.htm   A Punjabi website showing Mahunwal's Details]\n\n[[Category:Villages in Jalandhar district]]\n[[Category:Villages in Nakodar tehsil]]\n\n\n{{Jalandhar district}}\n\n\n{{Jalandhar-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{use Indian English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Mahunwal\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = Village \n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Punjab#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Punjab, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|31.110952|N|75.488333|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States an